WEBVTT

00:09.260 --> 00:13.180
Hi there! Welcome to
this video. Today we

00:13.180 --> 00:14.880
will learn what
private data is.

00:14.880 --> 00:17.160
Private data is
information about you

00:17.160 --> 00:20.000
that needs special
protection. When you

00:20.000 --> 00:22.160
understand private
data, you can make

00:22.160 --> 00:25.500
safer choices online.
The goal of this

00:25.500 --> 00:27.600
video is to help you
tell the difference

00:27.600 --> 00:31.280
between private data
and public data. We

00:31.280 --> 00:33.440
will look at examples
, explain why

00:33.440 --> 00:35.420
attackers and
companies want data,

00:35.420 --> 00:37.620
and practice a simple
rule you can use

00:37.620 --> 00:39.660
before you share
anything online.

00:44.680 --> 00:47.840
When you use apps,
games or websites,

00:47.840 --> 00:49.900
you often share
information,

00:49.900 --> 00:52.720
sometimes without
noticing. Some

00:52.720 --> 00:54.720
information is safe
to share, like your

00:54.720 --> 00:56.940
favourite colour.
Other information

00:56.940 --> 00:58.920
should stay private,
because it can

00:58.920 --> 01:01.680
identify you or help
someone reach you.

01:01.880 --> 01:04.540
Private data is
information about you

01:04.540 --> 01:06.660
that should only be
seen by you, your

01:06.660 --> 01:10.160
family or trusted
adults. Private data

01:10.160 --> 01:11.940
can help someone
figure out who you

01:11.940 --> 01:14.720
are or where you are.
That is why private

01:14.720 --> 01:17.920
data needs extra care
. Here are common

01:17.920 --> 01:20.720
examples of private
data. Your full name,

01:20.720 --> 01:22.580
your home address,
your phone number,

01:22.580 --> 01:25.060
your email address,
your school name, and

01:25.060 --> 01:28.020
your passwords. Even
one of these details

01:28.020 --> 01:30.460
can be important, and
several together can

01:30.460 --> 01:33.820
be very risky. Public
data is information

01:33.820 --> 01:36.160
that is usually okay
for most people to

01:36.160 --> 01:39.780
know. For example,
your favourite sport,

01:39.780 --> 01:41.940
your favourite food,
or your favourite

01:41.940 --> 01:45.240
movie. Public data is
still yours, but it

01:45.240 --> 01:47.160
normally does not
help someone find or

01:47.160 --> 01:49.780
identify you.
Sometimes the same

01:49.780 --> 01:52.020
information can be
safe in one situation

01:52.020 --> 01:55.700
and risky in another.
For example, a pet's

01:55.700 --> 01:57.840
name might seem
harmless, but it can

01:57.840 --> 01:59.980
be risky if someone
uses it to guess a

01:59.980 --> 02:05.640
password or security
question. A big

02:05.640 --> 02:08.020
privacy problem is
oversharing.

02:08.640 --> 02:11.060
Oversharing means
sharing too much, too

02:11.060 --> 02:14.120
often, or with too
many people. Even

02:14.120 --> 02:16.160
small details can
become risky when

02:16.160 --> 02:18.220
they are combined,
like your name plus

02:18.220 --> 02:20.400
your school plus your
location.

02:25.020 --> 02:27.260
Companies may collect
data to understand

02:27.260 --> 02:29.700
what you like and to
show you adverts or

02:29.700 --> 02:32.280
suggestions. They
might track what you

02:32.280 --> 02:34.580
click, what you watch
, and what you search

02:34.580 --> 02:37.780
for. This is one
reason privacy that

02:37.780 --> 02:39.460
privacy settings and
careful sharing are

02:39.460 --> 02:40.220
important.

02:44.760 --> 02:46.740
Attackers may want
private data for

02:46.740 --> 02:49.100
harmful reasons. They
might try to create

02:49.100 --> 02:51.580
fake accounts,
pretend to be you, or

02:51.580 --> 02:54.580
trick you later with
messages. That is why

02:54.580 --> 02:57.260
passwords and contact
details should never

02:57.260 --> 02:58.940
be shared with
strangers.

03:02.800 --> 03:05.900
Here is a simple rule
you can use. Stop and

03:05.900 --> 03:09.280
think before you
share. Ask yourself,

03:09.280 --> 03:11.980
who will see this?
Why do they want it?

03:11.980 --> 03:13.600
And what could go
wrong if the wrong

03:13.600 --> 03:16.380
person gets this
information? If you

03:16.380 --> 03:18.780
are unsure, the
safest choice is to

03:18.780 --> 03:22.040
ask a trusted adult.
Trusted adults can

03:22.040 --> 03:24.100
help you decide what
is private and what

03:24.100 --> 03:27.260
is public. Asking for
help is not a

03:27.260 --> 03:30.360
weakness. It is a
smart privacy skill.

03:34.720 --> 03:37.800
Let's recap. Private
data is information

03:37.800 --> 03:40.700
that can identify you
or help someone reach

03:40.700 --> 03:43.920
you. Public data data
is usually safe, like

03:43.920 --> 03:47.420
favourite things. And
context matters.

03:47.420 --> 03:49.440
Think carefully
before sharing,

03:49.440 --> 03:53.240
especially in games,
apps and messages. In

03:53.240 --> 03:55.180
class, you will
practice this with a

03:55.180 --> 03:58.040
sorting activity. You
will decide if

03:58.040 --> 04:00.480
examples belong in
the private column or

04:00.480 --> 04:03.560
the public column.
Remember, when in

04:03.560 --> 04:05.900
doubt, treat it as
private and ask a

04:05.900 --> 04:08.500
trusted adult. What
is private data?

04:08.500 --> 04:10.680
Great work. In this
video, you learned

04:10.680 --> 04:12.900
what private data is
and why it needs

04:12.900 --> 04:16.480
protection. Next,
watch the video about

04:16.480 --> 04:18.920
digital footprints to
learn what happens to

04:18.920 --> 04:21.820
data after it is
shared online. Thank

04:21.820 --> 04:22.400
you for watching.

